## **What You‚Äôll Need:**

* A Mac with an M1, M2, M3, M4 chip (Apple Silicon)  
* Stable Internet connection  
* 25‚Äì40 GB free space  
* 20‚Äì30 minutes of time  
* (Optional) anything to snack on

## **Step 1: Download Kali Linux ISO**

Head to the official **Kali Linux website**:

[*https://www.kali.org/get-kali/\#kali-platforms*](https://www.kali.org/get-kali/#kali-platforms)

Scroll to **Installer Images**

**![][image3]**

[*Direct link to Installer Images*](https://www.kali.org/get-kali/#kali-installer-images)

Under **‚ÄúApple Silicon (ARM64)‚Äù**, click **Download** under the recommended installer.

*This ISO is designed to run on Macs with Apple Silicon, so don‚Äôt download the regular x64 version ‚Äî it won‚Äôt work.*

## **Step 2: Download VMware Fusion**

VMware Fusion is now **free for personal use**. But since VMware is owned by Broadcom, you‚Äôll need to register to download it.

![][image4]

First, read the announcement here (optional ):  
[*VMware Fusion Now Free*](https://blogs.vmware.com/teamfusion/2024/05/fusion-pro-now-available-free-for-personal-use.html)

*T*hen head to the **download page**:  
[*Download VMware Fusion*](https://support.broadcom.com/group/ecx/productdownloads?subfamily=VMware+Fusion)

*![][image5]*

*![][image6]*

**Create a Broadcom account** (or log in if you already have one)

Accept the terms, verify your email, and you‚Äôll get access to the downloads.

Choose the **Apple Silicon version**, and click **Download**.

![][image8]

Once it‚Äôs downloaded, double-click the .dmg file to install VMware Fusion.

![][image9]

## **Step 3: Set Up Your Kali Virtual Machine**

**![][image10]**

Open **VMware Fusion** from Applications.

![][image11]

Choose: **‚ÄúInstall from disc or image‚Äù**

**![][image12]**

Drag and drop the **Kali ISO**, or click to browse and select it.

![][image13]

For OS type:

* Choose **Linux**  
* Version: **Debian 12** (since Kali is based on Debian)

![][image14]

Click **Customize Settings**, and name your VM something like Kali\_VM.

![][image15]

Next click on processor and memory and set it at 4096 and you can leave at 2 cores or 4 cores based on system

![][image16]

Then click back on show all and navigate to hard disk and set it as 45 or 50 gb

![][image17]

Then click back on show all and close it and then click on the play button icon

* **Memory (RAM)**: 4096 MB (4GB)  
* **CPU Cores**: 2 or 4 depending on your Mac  
* **Disk Size**: 45‚Äì50 GB

## **Step 4: Install Kali Linux (Graphical Installer)**

**![][image18]**

1. On the boot menu, use arrow keys to select **Graphical install** ‚Üí press **Enter**  
2. Follow the steps:

![][image19]

Language ‚Üí English (or your preference)

Region ‚Üí for timezone

Keyboard ‚Üí e.g. US

Set the system info:

![][image20]

Hostname ‚Üí kali

![][image21]

Domain name ‚Üí leave empty

![][image22]

Full name ‚Üí anything you like

![][image23]

Username ‚Üí your choice

Password ‚Üí strong one that you‚Äôll remember lol

Next,

Disk setup:

![][image24]

![][image25]

* Use **Guided ‚Äî use entire disk**  
* Select **All files in one partition**

**![][image26]**

* Choose **Yes** when asked to write changes  
* Let the install finish (it might take a few minutes)

![][image27]

* Choose **default software options**, then install GRUB when prompted.

Hit **Continue** to reboot once everything‚Äôs done.

## **Step 5: Boot into Kali & Enjoy**

**![][image28]**

After rebooting, you‚Äôll see the **Kali login screen**.

![][image29]

* Login with the **username and password you set**  
* Boom\! You‚Äôre in Kali on your Mac üéâ

Make sure you hit the terminal and run

*sudo apt upgrade*

*sudo apt update*
